## 5. Proposed Architecture

### 5.1 Decision Matrix

**A. Intent routing approach**

| Approach | Complexity | Runtime cost | Determinism | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Pure keyword/fuzzy matching (current `COMMAND_PHRASES`) | Low | Very low | High for exact phrasing, brittle otherwise | Keep as **fast-path layer only**, not sole router |
| Pure LLM free-text + substring parsing (current) | Low to build, high to maintain | One LLM call | Low — depends on model phrasing | Retire |
| Pure LLM function/tool calling | Medium | One LLM call | High, if model supports reliable tool-calling | Use for the "does this need a tool" decision |
| Dedicated small intent-classifier model | Medium-high (needs training data/fine-tune) | Very low (small model) | High | Not justified yet — no labeled data exists; revisit once usage logs accumulate (see Phase 11) |
| **Hybrid: deterministic fast-path + structured-output router LLM (recommended)** | Medium | Low for fast-path hits, one LLM call otherwise | High | **Recommended** |

*Recommendation:* Hybrid deterministic + LLM routing. The existing fuzzy matcher already proves that a large fraction of real commands are short, formulaic utterances — keep that as a zero-latency fast path, but replace the "then fall through to an LLM asked to emit a secret word" step with a router LLM constrained to structured JSON output (`{"route": "hardware_tool"|"knowledge_rag"|"general_chat"|"hybrid"|"clarify", "tool": ..., "parameters": {...}, "confidence": ...}`). This keeps the current system's good instinct (fast path for common phrases) while removing its failure mode (unstructured LLM parsing for everything else).

**B. Local RAG vector store**

| Option | Complexity | Fit for target hardware | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| ChromaDB (Python client) — same product already used in the Node.js BATU chatbot | Low (mirrors a design Ziad has already built and validated) | Good on a workstation/server; heavier on a Raspberry Pi | **Recommended for the primary/development deployment** |
| FAISS with a flat/IVF index persisted to disk | Medium (more manual metadata handling) | Lightest-weight, best fit if the assistant itself must run on-device on a Pi | Recommended fallback for constrained hardware |
| SQLite + `sqlite-vec`/cosine-in-Python | Low dependency footprint | Good for small corpora (the Smart City docs are ~15 files) | Viable minimal-dependency alternative |

*Recommendation:* ChromaDB, matching the pattern already proven in Chapter 6, unless the deployment target is confirmed to be memory-constrained (see missing information, §2.3), in which case fall back to FAISS with the same stage design.

**C. Reranking strategy**

| Option | Complexity | Requires network/API key | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| Cross-encoder API (Cohere rerank, as used in the Node chatbot) | Low to integrate | Yes — breaks "fully local whenever possible" | Optional enhancement only |
| Local cross-encoder model (e.g. a small sentence-transformers cross-encoder) | Medium (extra model to load) | No | **Recommended** |
| BM25-only fallback (as already implemented in the Node chatbot for the no-API case) | Low | No | Fallback if the cross-encoder model is too heavy for the hardware |

*Recommendation:* local cross-encoder reranker as primary, with the already-proven BM25 blend (40% vector similarity / 60% lexical) as the automatic fallback — directly reusing the weighting scheme validated in Chapter 6.

**D. Conversation memory storage**

| Option | Complexity | Verdict |
|---|---|---|
| In-process rolling list (session-only, lost on restart) | Very low | Minimum viable — required regardless of what else is added |
| SQLite-backed session store (durable across restarts) | Low | **Recommended** — cheap, local, matches "fully local" constraint |
| Redis (as used in the Node chatbot for caching) | Medium (new service to run) | Only justified if the voice assistant and RAG/chat backend are split into separate processes/services (see Phase 2) |

